reason: Both were relatively similar as far as difficulty is concerned. I think the vocab was just a little bit tougher just because some of the words weren't as easy to generalize as others. Subject: A199
reason: The map was more difficult to learn because the cue used was much less distinctive. With the Swahili words, I could use tools / similarities to English words in order to help me make the connection. For example, "afisi" sounded out in my head would sound a lot like "office." I used this same tool for most of the words, often playing off similar sounds or even related words that might help me make the distinction. Since there were no such connotations I could use with the map, it was much more difficult. Furthermore, I think that being able to respond in simple English words with the language section, such as "pants," etc. was much easier than having to learn the names of the cities, as I had never heard some of those words / word combinations before (even though they are still in English or at least derived from other European words). Thus, for that task I had to learn both the cue and the answer, whereas in the first one I only had to find a correlation.
